          "body": "The allocation of carts and oxen in verses 7-9 seems administrative at first read, but it encodes a theology of graduated holiness. Merari, who carries the heaviest structural loads (boards, bars, pillars, bases), receives the most carts — four — because the burden is greatest. Gershon, who carries the lighter fabric components, receives two. But Kohath receives nothing, not because their service is smallest but because their service is most holy: they carry the ark, the table, the lampstand, the altars — the *qodesh* items that must not be touched by cart or by unauthorized hands. The Kohathite principle anticipates 2 Samuel 6:3-7, where the cart-transport of the ark by David's men results in Uzzah's death. The graduated system of Numbers 7 is not bureaucratic fussiness; it is theological instruction about the danger of presumptuous proximity to the holy."
