          "title": "The anatomy of each leader's offering — burnt, sin, and peace",
          "body": "Each tribal offering is structured identically: silver and gold vessels filled with grain and incense for the altar's practical worship equipment; a burnt offering (bull, ram, yearling lamb) expressing total consecration; a sin offering (one male goat) making atonement; and peace offerings (two oxen, five rams, five male goats, five male lambs) enacting communal fellowship with God. The sequence is theologically ordered: consecration first, then atonement, then communion. No tribe attempts to feast before the burnt offering has ascended and the goat of sin offering has been slain. The peace offering is the largest in animal count precisely because fellowship with God — *shalom* — is the goal of the whole cultic system. The cumulative total of peace-offering animals (24 bulls, 60 rams, 60 goats, 60 lambs, 7:88) dwarfs the burnt-offering total (12 bulls, 12 rams, 12 lambs), suggesting that the altar's consecration is aimed at a people who feast before their God."
