          "title": "Chanukkah — dedication in Moses and in Maccabees",
          "body": "The word *chanukkah* (dedication) appears four times in this chapter (7:10, 11, 84, 88) and nowhere else in the Torah. It is not a common liturgical term in the Mosaic legislation — it is specific to this moment of altar inauguration. When the Maccabees re-dedicated the desecrated altar in Jerusalem in 165 BC (1 Maccabees 4:52-59) after Antiochus Epiphanes had defiled it, they deliberately named their celebration *Chanukkah* in conscious echo of Numbers 7. The Maccabean festival is not an invention; it is a typological re-enactment of the Mosaic dedication, claiming that God's altar, once defiled, can be re-consecrated and God's presence re-invited. The canonical connection between Numbers 7 and the later festival of Chanukkah reminds the reader that the theology of sacred space — its dedication, defilement, and restoration — runs from Sinai through the Second Temple period and into the New Covenant, where believers are called the temple of the Holy Spirit (1 Corinthians 3:16; 6:19)."
