          "title": "Verse 89 — the chapter's destination",
          "body": "Verse 89 stands alone at the end of the chapter with no ordinal number, no tribal leader, no offering list. Moses goes into the tent of meeting and hears a voice — *the* voice — speaking from above the *kapporet* (mercy seat) between the two cherubim on the ark of the testimony. The mercy seat (*kapporet*) is the cover of the ark, whose name derives from *kapar* (to cover, to atone) — the same root as Yom Kippur. This is the designated location of divine-human meeting (Exodus 25:22), and Numbers 7 ends by showing that location activated. Eighty-eight verses of human offering have prepared for one verse of divine speech. The chapter does not tell us what God said — that content is given in chapters 8-10. The point of verse 89 is not the content but the fact: when Israel consecrates the altar with obedient, equitable, costly worship, God speaks. Worship rightly offered is not merely dutiful performance; it is the creation of sacred conditions for encounter with the living God who speaks from between the cherubim."
